    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Another Path of Protection For the State's Drug Addicts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maia Szalavitz letter says 2000 New York State law permits sale of up to ten syringes withotu prescription, which could help addicts protect themselves from AIDS virus</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re: ''A Scorned Plan Seeks to Undo Needles and the Damage Done'' (Feb. 15), about proposed needle exchanges in Queens: The article states that such exchanges would need waivers from the Department of Health because it is illegal in New York State to hand out syringes without prescriptions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re: ''A Scorned Plan Seeks to Undo Needles and the Damage Done'' (Feb. 15), about proposed needle exchanges in Queens: The article states that such exchanges would need waivers from the Department of Health because it is illegal in New York State to hand out syringes without prescriptions.</p>
        <p>However, in 2000, the New York Assembly made it legal to sell up to 10 syringes without a prescription at pharmacies. It is crucial that addicts, particularly in communities where there has been opposition to needle exchange programs, be made aware of this law so they can protect themselves from H.I.V.</p>
        <p>MAIA SZALAVITZ  Upper East Side</p>
        <p>The writer is a co-author of ''Recovery Options: The Complete Guide.''</p>
      </block>
